WEBVTT

00:02.242 --> 00:16.481
I have the pleasure of talking to Bob Lacey, an old 
colleague, and want to chat with him about his

00:02.242 --> 00:16.481
experiences as one of the key people at A&M for a 
number of years. First, Bob, give us a brief

00:17.902 --> 00:26.433
summary of your biography up until you go to work at 
A&M. Where did you grow up? When did you get to A&M?

00:28.797 --> 00:29.678
What did you major in? And so forth. Okay. Well, I 
grew up in Centerville, Texas. Born October 6,

00:34.196 --> 00:36.380
1937. Went to public school in Centerville. 
Centerville is a small community of about 800

00:39.805 --> 00:43.790
people in Leon County. How many in the senior 
class? 28 in the senior class. I remarked there,

00:47.836 --> 00:50.841
we've never been anywhere. Chartered a bus to New 
Orleans and had our senior trip down there and was

00:51.722 --> 00:57.190
evicted out of two hotels in three days.

01:03.054 --> 01:17.589
But I graduated from high school in 1956 and came to 
Texas A&M in the fall of 1956 and majored in

01:03.054 --> 01:17.589
mathematics, which I got my degree in. Graduated 
in three and a half years, finished in January of

01:18.730 --> 01:24.696
1960. I really didn't know what I wanted to do, and 
my father, having been in the school business when

01:25.030 --> 01:40.447
he was a young man, he said, look, I always feel that 
a teaching certificate's a good thing for a person

01:25.030 --> 01:40.447
to have that particularly doesn't know what they 
want to do. So I stayed an extra semester and picked

01:40.467 --> 01:48.456
up the education courses that qualified me for a 
teaching certificate. I left A&M in the fall of 60

01:49.246 --> 01:56.435
and went down to Cypress Fairbanks High School. I 
taught math there for two years and decided that I

01:56.455 --> 02:10.712
wanted to get a graduate degree, primarily in the 
field of educational administration because I

01:56.455 --> 02:10.712
thought that I might make public school a career. 
And I received a leave of absence. from Tractor's

02:14.373 --> 02:16.516
Firebank, which I'm still on. And I came to A&M and 
needed some help in getting the finances for the

02:18.018 --> 02:26.870
master's degree. So I went over and knocked on Dr. 
Klippel's door. Dr. Klippel was head of the math

02:30.936 --> 02:33.480
department at that time. This would have been in 
the fall or the summer, rather, of 1961. And he

02:40.445 --> 02:44.231
said, yeah, we can use you as a teaching assistant. 
So they gave me a teaching assistant job, and I

02:44.251 --> 02:54.205
enrolled in the Master of Education 
Administration program. And I was a teaching

02:54.225 --> 03:03.799
assistant for two years, I believe, and graduated 
with my degree in 1963. And I still didn't know what

03:03.960 --> 03:09.608
I wanted to do, so Dr. Clipple indicated that I'd 
done a good job for him. He said, look, would you

03:12.930 --> 03:16.936
like to be put on as an instructor? I said, well, 
sure. So he gave me an instructor job. And I was one

03:21.523 --> 03:29.495
of the few that had the good fortune of being housed 
in Bagley Hall in my office. Bagley, you remember

03:29.515 --> 03:32.799
where Bagley was? But describe it for those who... 
Well, Bagley Hall was located over about where

03:32.820 --> 03:38.548
the... in the area where the Harrington Building 
is, or a little bit north of there, actually. And

03:47.684 --> 03:49.806
that's where the water tower was located on 
campus. And it was an old brick building, two

03:49.826 --> 03:56.553
stories, that had been there

03:49.826 --> 03:56.553
forever. Just like that building in the scene. And 
in the fall, excuse me, in the fall of 1964, After I

04:07.081 --> 04:18.173
finished my degree, I got a telephone call one day 
from Mr. Heaton, who was in the registrar.

04:20.196 --> 04:22.158
No, no, no. You were getting a call from Mr. Heaton? 
Oh, yeah. In December of 64, I got a telephone call

04:27.844 --> 04:32.329
from Mr. Heaton. and said that my name had been 
recommended to him as a possible replacement for

04:33.035 --> 04:46.496
an assistant registrar in the records section, 
and he'd like to talk to me. So I go over before the

04:46.516 --> 05:00.679
Christmas holidays and sit down and visit with 
him, and they had this opening, and he said, you

04:46.516 --> 05:00.679
have been recommended to me by the chairman of your 
master's committee and a couple of the committee

04:46.516 --> 05:00.679
members, which might be a possibility. And I'd 
like to talk to you about the job. Well, what the job

05:05.067 --> 05:14.224
entailed was maintaining the records of all of the 
students and the former students, the academic

05:05.067 --> 05:14.224
members, the former students, me and him. And it 
came quite a shock to me because I'd never done

05:14.244 --> 05:17.610
anything like this. I was really looking kind of 
forward to maybe getting back to the Cypress

05:17.730 --> 05:23.140
Firebank area in the second year or so. Anyway, I 
told him, I said, look, I need to think about this. I

05:27.478 --> 05:28.399
really don't know. I'm going off on a deer hunt down 
in South Texas, and while I'm out there in the

05:28.419 --> 05:33.724
woods, well, I'll be thinking. So I did, and what 
really had me puzzled was I knew nothing about any

05:33.744 --> 05:41.833
kind of administration. I worked in basically 
agriculture and teaching school. That's about

05:46.498 --> 05:48.300
all I've done. But anyway, I thought about it for a 
long time, and I came back and I talked to two or

05:49.293 --> 06:01.328
three of my old professors around here, and they 
said, look, it's an opportunity to take it. It

06:01.348 --> 06:01.748
doesn't work out. So I accepted the job and went to 
work in the registrar's office at the Central

06:01.769 --> 06:08.697
Registrar February 1, 1965. How much was that 
beginning salary? The beginning salary was,

06:11.701 --> 06:16.667
well, I was making $600 a month in the math 
department, And I was promised my same amount of

06:17.153 --> 06:23.422
money when I got over to the administration. But my 
first check, my salary was cut from $600 to $550 a

06:23.522 --> 06:28.909
month. And I never did really know the reason for 
that. But anyway, that was the wishes of the

06:32.234 --> 06:38.623
administrator in charge. And so I was happy with 
that. Describe the admissions and records staff

06:46.634 --> 06:50.460
and function when you joined? Okay, the entire 
operation was housed in the Richard Koch building

06:51.261 --> 07:09.250
on the first floor north side across the hall from 
the fiscal office and we occupied the basement,

06:51.261 --> 07:09.250
commonly referred to as the catacombs. We 
occupied half of the basement, actually. So we had

07:12.847 --> 07:17.891
half of the basement and half of the first floor. At 
that time, we had a registrar and director of

07:19.133 --> 07:23.416
admissions. Mr. Eaton carried both times. And we 
had an associate registrar, Ray Perriman, and an

07:26.139 --> 07:35.087
assistant registrar, Bob Lacey. And we had one 
excuse me, at that time we did not. Mr. Eaton was

07:40.994 --> 07:45.620
handling all of the admissions with the exception 
of Caroline Mitchell. Caroline Mitchell was an

07:45.640 --> 07:55.172
assistant director of admissions and she was in 
charge among many other duties she had. She was in

07:55.833 --> 07:59.778
charge of all the transfer, the undergraduate 
transfer. Reckon how many years of experience of

07:59.798 --> 08:05.124
A&M those people represented? At that time I'd say 
close to a hundred. Because they'd all been here.

08:12.834 --> 08:16.058
Because they'd all been there for a long, long, 
long time. Describe their personality and their

08:17.360 --> 08:23.027
each of them and their style of doing the job. Mr. 
Heaton was a very, very kind and considerate

08:25.210 --> 08:32.278
gentleman to work for. I found him as far as 
supervision with me, which I like very much. He

08:39.997 --> 08:48.606
expected us to get our job done, yet he didn't 
constantly

08:39.997 --> 08:48.606
stay close to us. He gave me a job and we were to do it, 
and we did it. He always gave us the strong support

08:54.953 --> 09:03.402
and the backup that we needed. Caroline Mitchell 
was a very strong-willed personality lady.

09:16.486 --> 09:30.549
Caroline had a number of functions, and this will 
probably shock you when you think about what we

09:16.486 --> 09:30.549
have today, but not only was she in charge of the 
transfer students, she was in charge of building

09:16.486 --> 09:30.549
the master schedule of classes. She was the editor 
of the catalog. She assigned all of the classroom

09:33.916 --> 09:38.100
teaching space on the campus. And she ran the 
summer orientation, the freshman orientation

09:38.981 --> 09:46.067
conferences. She had two clerical type . Mr. 
Perriman was the associate registrar, and of

09:49.911 --> 09:58.839
course I reported to him for a while. And his basic 
responsibilities had to do with the overall

10:02.840 --> 10:10.515
operation of the registrar's office related to 
the record section. And I guess his main

10:10.955 --> 10:20.173
responsibility, which was quite heavy in those 
days, was the residency factor. hadn't

10:20.677 --> 10:34.230
determined whether or not a student was to have 
residence, had state residency, or whether to be

10:20.677 --> 10:34.230
classified as a resident. And then he was also, 
over

10:34.250 --> 10:39.715
all the clerical functions that aided him, 
residency as well. And also he was in charge of

10:39.735 --> 10:41.877
graduation, too. I forgot about that, which at 
that time was quite a chore because of the way in

10:41.897 --> 10:49.705
which he was. The enrollment at Texas A&M in 1965, 
if my memory serves me correctly, was somewhere, I

10:50.782 --> 11:09.566
think, around 8,000

10:50.782 --> 11:09.566
to 10,000, maybe 12,000. I'm not too certain about 
that. We hadn't grown a whole lot. We were coming

11:14.472 --> 11:20.620
out of the era of all-male, all-military change in 
1963, so a few years after that. Who did the

11:21.325 --> 11:24.453
admissions? Mr. Heaton did most of the 
admissions. Shortly after I came, they did hire

11:29.467 --> 11:34.320
another admissions assistant. It was a fellow by 
the name of Bob Gleason. Bob handled the freshman

11:37.998 --> 11:45.310
undergraduates, and Caroline handled the 
transfer students. Of course, as you well know,

11:45.330 --> 11:58.371
graduate admissions, although our office was 
responsible for the record keeping of the

11:45.330 --> 11:58.371
applications of Bob and Lewis and all that sort of 
stuff, that determination was made in the

11:45.330 --> 11:58.371
graduate college. Now, all of the technological

12:05.842 --> 12:08.987
work was done on typewriters then? All of it. All of 
it. Was some of it done by hand still? No. Well, when

12:16.037 --> 12:24.710
I came there, the posting of the academic record, I 
assume that's basically one of the main things.

12:25.652 --> 12:31.140
The posting of the academic record was done by 
punch cards down at the computer center, being

12:31.694 --> 12:38.102
generated on each student after the professor 
turned in their grades. The grades at that time

12:38.122 --> 12:44.089
were turned in on IBM cards, but they were written 
in. In other words, Joe Doe in Math 102, Section

12:44.109 --> 12:51.798
500, the professor would put his grade on there and 
sign his name. And also at that time, we kept

12:51.818 --> 12:56.885
absentees on all of our students. Those IBM cards 
were then key punched. at the computer center. The

13:02.490 --> 13:11.903
data punched in, geared to the student 
identification number, and then were sorted in

13:02.490 --> 13:11.903
order of the student's name. And all of these were 
taking six courses and they all came together

13:12.143 --> 13:17.190
under his name. And at that time, all of the 
permanent academic records were transported to

13:17.210 --> 13:27.604
the computer center by means of the assistant 
registrar And at night, these were run, and you'd

13:28.225 --> 13:32.890
have to stay there for security reasons. And each 
one of these things were then printed on the

13:32.910 --> 13:36.995
student's academic record. Quite a horrendous 
task. And one of the first things that I got

13:40.239 --> 13:46.526
interested in was a faster and better way to do 
that. So I was able to do a lot of visitations and

13:46.546 --> 13:53.895
whatnot, find what they call a heat transfer 
posting method. And that permitted us then to have

13:54.449 --> 14:00.416
a carbon tape run at the computer center after 
these shorts were made. And then we could post the

14:00.436 --> 14:07.885
records in our office, and that stopped us from 
having to take them out. And it was done in one

14:07.905 --> 14:12.651
swoop, one stamp, and the entire semester was on 
the students' records. How long did that run take?

14:15.254 --> 14:22.903
To do it by heat transfer, we could do it in about 
three or four days, as opposed to about two weeks of

14:15.254 --> 14:22.903
what they were doing earlier. And obviously that 
speeded up the delivery of transcripts that

14:23.457 --> 14:32.609
students were in great need for at the end of the 
semester. We started to give much faster

14:32.629 --> 14:37.935
turnaround on our transcripts. One thing that I 
think might be interesting in this that I forgot to

14:38.035 --> 14:52.654
tell you when I was hired, the reason that I was 
hired was that the assistant registrar that was in

14:38.035 --> 14:52.654
charge, or that had the position that Mr. Heaton 
talked to me about, had taken a bribe from some of

14:53.377 --> 15:04.750
our foreign students at that time to change 
grades.

15:04.770 --> 15:20.127
And in time this surfaced and charges were brought 
against the Assistant Registrar and there was a

15:04.770 --> 15:20.127
trial and he was given a suspended sentence I think 
for five to six years. Mr. Rutter, of course, was

15:20.815 --> 15:24.140
the president of the university at that time. And 
when Mr. Heaton made the offer to me, he told me that

15:24.961 --> 15:38.261
there would be a complete investigation of my 
background from day one until now, now being in 65.

15:39.923 --> 15:41.866
And I said fine. I thought I could withstand that. 
Several years after that, after I got to know a lot

15:45.335 --> 16:03.234
of people around there, particularly the folks 
over at security, Chief Ed Powell, who was chief of

15:45.335 --> 16:03.234
security at that time, and I were having coffee one 
day, and he said, Bob, he said, I know you real well

15:45.335 --> 16:03.234
now, and he said, I'm going to tell you something. 
He said, what's that? He said, Mr. Rutter ordered

16:05.396 --> 16:14.346
an investigation of you by the FBI, the Texas 
Department of Public Safety, the Brazos County

16:14.714 --> 16:32.174
Sheriff's Department and our security here, and 
said in all those years from date of birth until

16:14.714 --> 16:32.174
1965, we found that you had a speeding ticket 
issued to you between Austin and San Antonio in

16:14.714 --> 16:32.174
1957. I said, that is correct. And so it was quite a, 
obviously, Mr. Rutter, this caused the

16:35.738 --> 16:43.928
university a lot of embarrassment, as you can well 
imagine. So he wanted to be sure and having, as you

16:44.228 --> 16:55.966
well know, the military background he had, I think 
that made it even more important to him that this

16:44.228 --> 16:55.966
check be done. All of us that knew Mr. Heaton knew 
him as a very special person. When did he begin his

17:03.278 --> 17:06.002
work with the university? Do you know? I think it 
was in the very late 30s or early 40s. Mr. Heaton got

17:13.351 --> 17:24.744
his undergraduate degree, I believe, at Stephen 
F. Austin State University in Nacogdoches, and he

17:13.351 --> 17:24.744
came here to get a master's degree. He was enrolled 
in a master's program here, and I believe began

17:24.764 --> 17:35.616
work in the registrar's office at that time, and 
was hired I am not I'm not certain that he came as an

17:36.153 --> 18:03.696
assistant or if he just had part-time work but I 
believe he followed a man named Charlie Friday as a

17:36.153 --> 18:03.696
regular guard so late 30s or early 40s for me as a 
junior faculty member in the 60s I thought

17:36.153 --> 18:03.696
apparently he had come at the beginning of time 
well it seemed like he's been here forever right I

18:03.980 --> 18:07.624
never saw him without a tie on, his shirt and tie. I 
never thought of him as engaging in much small

18:09.926 --> 18:19.876
talk, but I never was around him when he wasn't 
pleasant. Always pleasant. You're absolutely

18:21.378 --> 18:22.739
correct. As a matter of fact, the few times that I 
